---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Solar Twins - ArXiv Atlas";
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <div class="page-header">
      <h1>Solar Twins</h1>
      <div class="page-meta">
        <span class="tag">Stellar Populations</span>
        <span class="tag">Galactic Evolution</span>
        <span class="tag">Chemical Tagging</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="content">
      <h2 id="section-0">Overview</h2>
      <p>
        Solar twins are stars with atmospheric parameters nearly identical to the Sun: 
        <strong>|ΔT<sub>eff</sub>| < ~100 K</strong>, <strong>|Δlog g| < 0.1 dex</strong>, 
        and <strong>|Δ[Fe/H]| < 0.1 dex</strong>. These stars share nearly solar metallicities 
        while spanning a wide range of ages, making them powerful tracers of Galactic disk evolution.
      </p>

      <h2 id="section-1">Key Properties</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Parameter matching:</strong> T<sub>eff</sub> ≈ 5777 K, log g ≈ 4.44, [Fe/H] ≈ 0.0</li>
        <li><strong>High-quality sample:</strong> 6,594 solar twins identified in Gaia DR3 GSP-Spec within ~300 pc</li>
        <li><strong>Typical offsets:</strong> ΔT<sub>eff</sub> ~ tens of K; Δ[Fe/H] ≤ 0.05 dex for highest-quality subset</li>
        <li><strong>Age span:</strong> From young stars to ages exceeding the Sun's ~4.6 Gyr</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="section-2">Age Distribution &amp; Migration</h2>
      <p>
        The age distribution of local solar twins reveals two distinct features after deconvolving selection effects:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>~2 Gyr peak:</strong> A narrow peak corresponding to a relatively recent burst of star formation in the local disk</li>
        <li><strong>4–6 Gyr bump:</strong> A broad feature closely associated with the Sun's birth epoch</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The presence of many 4–6 Gyr old twins in the solar neighborhood challenges predictions of a 
        <strong>corotation barrier</strong> built by the Galactic bar, which was thought to prevent stars 
        born inside R<sub>GC</sub> ~6 kpc from reaching the solar neighborhood. This suggests the Sun's 
        long-distance (≥3 kpc) radial migration is shared by many inner disk stars, possibly linked to 
        the epoch of bar formation.
      </p>

      <h2 id="section-3">Scientific Applications</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Differential abundance studies:</strong> Precise benchmarks for comparing stellar abundances</li>
        <li><strong>Age-dating:</strong> Calibrating isochrones and stellar evolution models</li>
        <li><strong>Spectroscopic calibration:</strong> Testing and validating survey pipelines (APOGEE, GALAH)</li>
        <li><strong>Migration studies:</strong> Tracing radial mixing and dynamical evolution of the disk</li>
        <li><strong>Star formation history:</strong> Reconstructing local and inner disk SFH from age distributions</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="section-4">Open Questions</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>How efficient is radial migration across the corotation barrier over cosmic time?</li>
        <li>What is the exact connection between bar formation and enhanced inner disk star formation?</li>
        <li>Can solar twins trace chemical abundance gradients at birth vs. present day?</li>
        <li>How do selection effects in spectroscopic surveys bias the twin sample?</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="references">
        <h2 id="section-5">Key References</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Gaia DR3 GSP-Spec solar twins catalog (2603.11155). 
            <a href="/papers/2603.11155_solar-twins.html">paper page</a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Related Concepts</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/concepts/galaxy-bimodality">Galaxy bimodality</a> — stellar populations and disk evolution</li>
        <li><a href="/concepts/cosmic-web-gas-accretion">Cosmic-web gas accretion</a> — fuel for star formation</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
